have moderated somewhat in 2025. I'm also pulling together the balance sheet data to get a sense of the asset base. Looking at the cash flow metrics, operating cash flow has grown steadily from $8.7B in 2021 to $17.54B in 2024, with 2025 expected around $16-17B despite increased capital expenditures. Capital spending jumped significantly to $6.55B in 2024 due to the Catalent acquisition, up from roughly $2.5B the prior year.\n\nFor free cash flow, I'm working through the numbers—2024 came in at $10.70B, which represents an 11.31% decline from 2023, putting the prior year at approximately $12.07B. I'm noticing the Catalent acquisition inflated 2024 capex, so I should back that out to get a clearer picture of underlying capital spending. For 2025, I'm estimating operating cash flow around $17-18B with capex of $8-10B, which gives me a projected FCF range of $8-10B. Now I'm breaking down the segment revenues for 2025 by converting from DKK to USD. Looking at the rest of Novo Nordisk's product portfolio, Rybelsus is pulling in around $3.2B, while their older obesity drug Saxenda is fading as Wegovy dominates that market. Their insulin products like NovoRapid and Tresiba still contribute meaningfully at $2.5B and $1.8B respectively, though they're being overshadowed by the GLP-1 boom. Geographically, North America is their cash cow at 58% of revenue, with international markets and China making up the remainder. Comparing to Eli Lilly's valuation metrics, they're trading at a 25x P/E with an EV/EBITDA around 22x.\n\nNow looking at the competitive landscape, Novo's valuation has compressed dramatically from the 35-40x multiples they commanded in 2023-2024 down to just 12x P/E currently, which looks extremely cheap relative to their history. Their enterprise value sits around $195B when accounting for net debt, giving them an EV/EBITDA of roughly 8.6x. Meanwhile, Sanofi and other competitors are trading in similar ranges, though AstraZeneca commands a premium at 18-20x P/E. The analyst consensus remains cautious with most calling it a hold, and Goldman Sachs specifically has a neutral rating with a $41 price target.\n\nLooking at the price targets across the Street, Morgan Stanley and JPMorgan are also neutral, while Cantor Fitzgerald is the outlier at $160, suggesting the consensus sits somewhere in the $65-85 range depending on the source. On valuation metrics, Novo's trading at roughly 11.8x forward P/E on 2025 earnings, which would expand slightly to 13.1x if earnings decline 10% next year. The EV/EBITDA multiple of 8.6x and price-to-FCF of 17.1x both suggest the market is pricing in significant headwinds.\n\nNovo was founded back in 1923 in Denmark and trades on both the Copenhagen exchange and as an ADR on the NYSE. The company has around 75,000 employees and recently brought in Maziar Doustdar as CEO in August 2025. Looking at the pipeline, CagriSema showed 22.7% weight loss in Phase 3 but fell short of the 25% target, while they're awaiting FDA review on the 25mg oral semaglutide formulation for obesity. They've also licensed UBT251, a triple agonist from United Labs that's in early development, and have Amycre in the pipeline as well.\n\nBeyond the GLP-1 space, they've got Insulin icodec (Awiqli) which just got approved as a once-weekly basal insulin option, plus hemophilia treatments like Mim8 and marstacimab in Phase 3. The real headwinds though are the patent expirations hitting India and Canada in early 2026 with generics coming in, intense competition from Eli Lilly's tirzepatide products which are showing better efficacy, and the CagriSema disappointment. There's also mounting price pressure on GLP-1s from US drug price negotiations and potential Medicare/Medicaid cuts, which is why they're guiding for a 5-13% sales decline in 2026 on top of the CEO transition risk.\n\nThe Catalent acquisition debt is creating manufacturing ramp-up costs, and I'm noticing their pipeline is heavily concentrated on semaglutide variants which adds execution risk. On the positive side, the obesity market is massive at over $100B addressable, aging populations are a tailwind, and there's emerging data on cardiovascular benefits and potential Alzheimer's applications. The near-term catalysts are oral semaglutide obesity approval, CagriSema readouts, and cardiovascular outcomes data that could unlock new indications.\n\nNow I'm building out the investment thesis. Novo Nordisk has created two blockbuster drugs generating roughly $30B in combined annual sales, but the stock has been hammered from $81 down to $41 as the market prices in patent cliffs, Eli Lilly's competitive threat, and that 2026 guidance cut. At 11.8x forward earnings, it's trading well below its historical 30x average and cheaper than healthcare peers, suggesting the bear case is already baked in. The real opportunity is if oral obesity approval comes through, CagriSema finds a path forward, and they can expand into new indications—all while their century-long insulin heritage provides a stable foundation. This looks like a quality company hitting a temporary growth wall at a historically attractive price.\n\nNow I'm mapping out the valuation scenarios to stress-test the thesis. Writing the Python script... I'm working through the revenue breakdown for 2024 and 2025 — calculating Rare Disease as the remainder after accounting for Diabetes and Obesity segments, then cross-referencing with the 2025 projections showing growth in Obesity Care and modest increases in Rare Disease.\n\nNow I'm backing into 2023 figures to establish the historical trend, breaking down the GLP-1 diabetes portfolio by individual products and converting from DKK to USD, then estimating insulin revenue separately to build out the full year picture.\n\nFor 2022 and 2021, I'm working with less granular data, so I'm estimating the revenue split based on what I know about product launch timing and market dynamics—Wegovy was brand new in 2022, so obesity care was minimal, while diabetes dominated the portfolio.\n\nLooking at operating margins, there's a notable compression from 45% in 2024 down to 37% in 2025, which likely reflects the integration costs from the Catalent acquisition, elevated R&D spending on programs like CagriSema, and higher operating expenses overall. Now I'm cross-checking the depreciation and amortization figures—the $5.2B gap between EBITDA and operating income aligns with the Catalent acquisition and intangible amortization, so I'll incorporate these numbers into the script. Let me also verify the ROE calculation against the equity figures to ensure consistency.\n\nChecking my ROE math for both years—2025 comes in around 63.4% which matches the reported 61%, and 2024 hits 80.9% against the stated 80.8%, so the equity and net income figures are tracking correctly. Now I'm calculating ROA by dividing net income by average assets for both periods.\n\nThe ROIC numbers show a significant decline from 46% in 2024 down to 21% in 2025, which makes sense given that the Catalent acquisition substantially increased the company's invested capital base. For the WACC calculation, I'm using a beta of 0.6 for a pharma company like Novo Nordisk, which gives me a cost of equity around 7.6% when combined with the current risk-free rate and equity risk premium, then blending that with an after-tax cost of debt of roughly 3% weighted by the capital structure to arrive at a WACC of approximately 5.7%.\n\nThat brings me to about 6.5% when I factor in the remaining components. The economic spread between the 21% ROIC and 6.5% WACC is a healthy 14.5 percentage points, which indicates the company is creating substantial value. Now I'm looking at how Novo Nordisk's valuation multiples compare to its peers—Eli Lilly is trading at a significant premium with a 30x P/E, while companies like Sanofi and Novo Nordisk itself are much cheaper at 10-12x P/E, suggesting there's a wide range of valuations across the pharma sector depending on growth prospects and market positioning.\n\nWhen I calculate Novo Nordisk's actual 2025 trailing P/E using the current stock price and EPS, I get about 11.83x, which is indeed quite attractive. The enterprise value calculation shows roughly $195.4 billion, and dividing that by the 2025 EBITDA of $22.66 billion gives an EV/EBITDA of 8.63x. This is striking because the company traded at 25-35x EV/EBITDA just a couple of years ago, so the current valuation appears to be pricing in significant pessimism about future earnings despite the company's quality.\n\nNow I'm running through three scenarios to value the stock: a bear case where 2026 revenue declines 13% before recovery, a base case with a 5% decline and gradual recovery, and a bull case assuming successful oral Wegovy approval and positive CagriSema data. These scenarios give me a range from $35 to $75 per share. With this comprehensive valuation picture in place, I'm ready to structure the analysis using the Berkshire template and applying Novo Nordisk's brand colors—a deep navy, mid-blue, and light blue palette. I'm settling on the same color palette as the existing project for consistency, then mapping out the complete Excel workbook structure with 12 tabs covering everything from the cover sheet through market sentiment, including detailed financial statements, management profiles, risk analysis, and valuation metrics.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":878,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1112,"cache_read_input_tokens":81355,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1112},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c2f9e2bf-4eb3-44bc-922b-8db97158fefa","uuid":"556288a6-a1d6-4637-8c1b-3668ba5d8965"}
